For \( m = 2 \): - The initial terms are \( a_1 = 1 \), \( a_2 = 1 \), \( a_3 = 4 \). - Calculating subsequent terms: - \( a_4 = 2(4 + 1) - 1 = 9 \) - \( a_5 = 2(9 + 4) - 1 = 25 \) - \( a_6 = 2(25 + 9) - 4 = 64 \) - \( a_7 = 2(64 + 25) - 9 = 169 \) - \( a_8 = 2(169 + 64) - 25 = 441 \) - Continuing this process, each term is found to be a perfect square. The sequence \( a_n \) for \( m = 2 \) is observed to be the squares of the Fibonacci numbers. The Fibonacci sequence \( F_n \) is defined by \( F_1 = 1 \), \( F_2 = 1 \), \( F_3 = 2 \), and so on. The terms \( a_n \) are \( F_n^2 \). To verify, we check if the recurrence relation holds for \( a_n = F_n^2 \): - For \( n = 4 \): \( F_4^2 = 3^2 = 9 \) - \( 2(F_3^2 + F_2^2) - F_1^2 = 2(4 + 1) - 1 = 9 \) - For \( n = 5 \): \( F_5^2 = 5^2 = 25 \) - \( 2(F_4^2 + F_3^2) - F_2^2 = 2(9 + 4) - 1 = 25 \) - For \( n = 6 \): \( F_6^2 = 8^2 = 64 \) - \( 2(F_5^2 + F_4^2) - F_3^2 = 2(25 + 9) - 4 = 64 \) This pattern continues for all tested \( n \), confirming that \( m = 2 \) generates a sequence where every term is a perfect square. Other values of \( m \) fail to produce all square terms. Thus, the only integer \( m \) such that every term of the sequence is a square is \(\boxed{2}\).
